DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(83)90044-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199683900442
AB  - Tariff impacts are examined assuming the domestic and foreign producers are oligopolistically interdependent and both domestic and foreign transportation costs are significant. The imposition of a tariff in this spatial duopoly: (1) has a distributional impact under all three conjectural variations considered, in that the delivered prices paid by customers of the foreign firm increase by more than the delivered prices paid by customers of the protected domestic firm; and (2) under some types of oligopolistic behavior, the domestic firm may lower its price when protected by a tariff - that is, the Metzler paradox may arise in a partial equilibrium context.
